#include <string.h>
int isBalanced(char* str) {
    char stack[1000];
    int top = -1;
    for (int i = 0; i < strlen(str); i++) {
        if (str[i] == '(' || str[i] == '{' || str[i] == '[') {
            stack[++top] = str[i];
        } else {
            if (top == -1) return 0;
            char c = stack[top--];
            if ((str[i] == ')' && c != '(') || 
                (str[i] == '}' && c != '{') || 
                (str[i] == ']' && c != '['))
                return 0;
        }
    }
    return top == -1;
}
```
Push opening brackets onto stack. For each closing bracket, pop and check if it matches. At the end, stack should be empty. Time: O(n), Space: O(n).

```c
int binarySearch(int arr[], int n, int target) {
    int low = 0, high = n - 1;
    while (low <= high) {
        int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;
        if (arr[mid] == target)
            return mid;
        else if (arr[mid] < target)
            low = mid + 1;
        else
            high = mid - 1;
    }
    return -1;
}
```
Binary search works on sorted arrays by repeatedly halving the search space. Time: O(log n), Space: O(1). Note: mid = low + (high-low)/2 prevents integer overflow compared to (low+high)/2.

```c
struct Node* findMiddle(struct Node* head) {
    struct Node *slow = head, *fast = head;
    while (fast != NULL && fast->next != NULL) {
        slow = slow->next;
        fast = fast->next->next;
    }
    return slow;
}
```
Use slow (1 step) and fast (2 steps) pointers. When fast reaches the end, slow is at the middle. Time: O(n), Space: O(1). For even-length lists, this returns the second middle element.

